# Heavy / Multi-File Tasks

Edit files directly, one at a time. No throwaway scripts, batch processors, or regex bulk-replace for repo changes.

## Chunk order

1. **Dependency order** — types/contracts → server → app wiring → UI
2. **Layer order** (see `agent-discipline.mdc`) — `apps/app` / Storybook before `packages/design-system/components/ui/`
3. **Finish one chunk** before starting the next; no partial edits across the repo

Report progress plainly: "Updated 5 of 12 files".

## Next.js chunks (`apps/app/**`)

Training data is stale — use MCP docs, not memory (Next.js `/docs/app/guides/ai-agents`).

After each logical chunk touching `apps/app`:

1. `pnpm --filter app typecheck` (narrow gate first)
2. Dev server up → `nextjs_index` → `nextjs_call` `get_errors` on port `3000`
3. Unsure about APIs → `nextjs-docs://llms-index` → `nextjs_docs`

Full gates: `nextjs-mcp-quality.mdc`. Point MCP `init` at `apps/app`, not repo root.

## Do not

- Create `update.py`, `migrate.js`, `refactor.sh`, or one-off codemods for the task
- Propose sed/regex commands for the user to run across the tree
- Generate migration guides or checkpoint files unless asked
- Blindly pattern-match — read each file's context

## Allowed automation

Permanent infra only: Biome, test runners, ORM migrations, CI/deploy — not temporary facilitators.

For 100+ files with complex logic, suggest IDE refactor tools; still edit file-by-file if the user prefers.

## Scale

| Files | Approach |
|-------|----------|
| ≤10 | Edit all sequentially |
| 11–30 | Batches of ~5–10, verify between batches |
| 30+ | Group by module/feature; MCP/typecheck per group when touching `apps/app` |
